# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: arm-ball
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:arm-ball/akeal-hosein] Born in Port of Spain, Hosein represented the West Indies under-19s at the 2012 Under-19 World Cup in Australia.
[src:arm-ball/akeal-hosein] His first-class debut for Trinidad and Tobago came during the 2012–13 Regional Four Day Competition, against Jamaica.
[src:arm-ball/akeal-hosein] The following season, Hosein was man of the match in consecutive games, taking 6/33 and 5/34 against the Windward Islands and then scoring a maiden first-class century, 102 not out, against the Leewards.
[src:arm-ball/akeal-hosein] He subsequently signed with the Barbados Tridents for the 2014 Caribbean Premier League, and has since made appearances for the team at the 2014 Champions League Twenty20 and the 2015 CPL tournaments.
[src:arm-ball/akeal-hosein] In November 2019, he was named in Trinidad and Tobago's squad for the 2019–20 Regional Super50 tournament.
[src:arm-ball/akeal-hosein] In July 2020, he was named in the Trinbago Knight Riders squad for the 2020 Caribbean Premier League.
[src:arm-ball/akeal-hosein] On 23 December 2022, he was bought by Sunrisers Hyderabad for IPL 2023.
[src:arm-ball/akeal-hosein] He was released by them in November 2023 after just one season.
[src:arm-ball/akeal-hosein] In 2023, Hosein was signed to play for the Quetta Gladiators in the 9th edition of the Pakistani Super League.
[src:arm-ball/akeal-hosein] On 8 March 2024, during a game against Peshawar Zalmi, Hosein took a hat-trick, dismissing Aamer Jamal, Mehran Mumtaz and Luke Wood in three consecutive deliveries, becoming only the sixth bowler to take a hat-trick in the PSL.
[src:arm-ball/akeal-hosein] In December 2020, Hosein was named in the West Indies' One Day International (ODI) squad for their series against Bangladesh.
[src:arm-ball/akeal-hosein] He made his ODI debut for the West Indies, against Bangladesh, on 20 January 2021.
[src:arm-ball/akeal-hosein] In February 2021, he was named in the West Indies' Twenty20 International (T20I) squad for their series against Sri Lanka.
[src:arm-ball/akeal-hosein] In May 2021, Akeal was given a white-ball central contract by the Cricket West Indies for the 2020–21 season.
[src:arm-ball/akeal-hosein] He was one of the 10 players to be given a white-ball central contract for the 2020–21 season.
[src:arm-ball/akeal-hosein] In June 2021, he was added to the West Indies' Twenty20 International (T20I) squad for their series against South Africa.
[src:arm-ball/akeal-hosein] He made his T20I debut on 3 July 2021, for the West Indies against South Africa.
[src:arm-ball/akeal-hosein] In July 2021, he was included in the West Indies squad to play the last two T20Is against Australia.
[src:arm-ball/akeal-hosein] In September 2021, Hosein was named as one of four reserve players in the West Indies' squad for the 2021 ICC Men's T20 World Cup.
[src:arm-ball/akeal-hosein] In October 2021, Hosein was added to the West Indies' 2021 ICC Men's T20 World Cup squad replacing Fabian Allen who was ruled out with an ankle injury.
[src:arm-ball/akeal-hosein] In May 2024, he was named in the West Indies squad for the 2024 ICC Men's T20 World Cup tournament.
[src:arm-ball/arm-ball] An **arm ball** is a type of delivery in cricket.
[src:arm-ball/arm-ball] It is a variation delivery bowled by an off spin bowler or slow left-arm orthodox bowler.
[src:arm-ball/arm-ball] It is the finger spin equivalent of a wrist spinner's *slider* or *zooter*.
[src:arm-ball/arm-ball] In contrast to the stock delivery, an arm ball is delivered by rolling the fingers down the back of the ball on release.
[src:arm-ball/arm-ball] This puts backspin onto the ball, which does not turn appreciably off the pitch.
[src:arm-ball/arm-ball] Instead, it travels straight on in the direction of the arm.
[src:arm-ball/arm-ball] By keeping the seam upright, the bowler can also hope to obtain some outswing away from the right-handed batsman, thereby confusing the batsman who expects the ball to turn.
[src:arm-ball/arm-ball] The arm ball is often used as a surprise variation by an off spinner who is turning the ball considerably.
[src:arm-ball/arm-ball] A complacent or poorly skilled batsman playing for the expected spin can be taken by surprise and get out bowled or lbw, or edge the ball with the outside edge of the bat to offer a catch to the wicket-keeper or slip fielders.
[src:arm-ball/arm-ball] Offspinners Harbhajan Singh, Graeme Swann and Mohammad Hafeez have excelled in bowling arm balls.
[src:arm-ball/arm-ball] The arm ball has also been employed with a great deal of success over the years by left-arm orthodox bowlers.
[src:arm-ball/arm-ball] In this case, the stock ball will turn away from the right-handed batsman and the arm-ball would swing in, allowing the bowler to beat the inside edge of the bat and attack the stumps.
[src:arm-ball/arm-ball] Hedley Verity in particular was well known for his fast inswinging arm-ball, often bowled at yorker length.
[src:arm-ball/arm-ball] Daniel Vettori, Rangana Herath and Derek Underwood are other examples of left-arm orthodox bowlers renowned for use of an inswinging arm ball to good effect.
[src:arm-ball/arm-ball] Vettori famously bowled Darren Maddy with a perfect arm ball at the Oval Test Match of 1999.
[src:arm-ball/arm-ball] Having set up Maddy with two balls breaking away from him, Vettori then bowled a perfectly disguised arm ball.
[src:arm-ball/arm-ball] Thinking the ball was another stock delivery, Maddy left it, only to see it swing in and strike his off-stump.
[src:arm-ball/arm-ball] Some recent examples of left-arm orthodox spinners who have excelled in bowling arm balls are Ravindra Jadeja, Axar Patel, Akeal Hosein, Shakib Al Hasan, Sophie Ecclestone and Sai Kishore.
[src:arm-ball/axar-patel] He made his ODI debut on 15 June 2014 against Bangladesh.
[src:arm-ball/axar-patel] He was selected in India's 15-man squad for the 2015 Cricket World Cup held in Australia and New Zealand.
[src:arm-ball/axar-patel] He made his Test debut for India against England on 13 February 2021, where he took 7 wickets.
[src:arm-ball/axar-patel] He became the ninth bowler for India to take a five-wicket haul on debut in Test cricket.
[src:arm-ball/axar-patel] In his second first-class match, against Delhi in November 2013, Patel took 6 for 55 in the first innings.
[src:arm-ball/axar-patel] Patel played just one first-class game in his debut season for Gujarat, but had a more successful showing in 2013.
[src:arm-ball/axar-patel] Slotted primarily as a bowling allrounder, the left-arm spinner got his first IPL contract with Mumbai Indians ahead of IPL 2013, although he was on the bench for the entire season, the team won the title in that year.
[src:arm-ball/axar-patel] He was one of the key contributors to India Under-23s' title win in the 2013 ACC Emerging Teams Cup, with seven wickets, including a four-for in the semi-final against UAE.
[src:arm-ball/axar-patel] He was one of the consistent performers for Gujarat in the 2013/14 Ranji Trophy, finishing the season with 369 runs at an average of 46.12 and 29 wickets at 23.58.
[src:arm-ball/axar-patel] In early 2014, he was named the BCCI Under-19 cricketer of the year for the 2012/13 season.
[src:arm-ball/axar-patel] In August 2019, he was named in the India Red team's squad for the 2019–20 Duleep Trophy.
[src:arm-ball/axar-patel] In October 2019, he was named in India C's squad for the 2019–20 Deodhar Trophy.
[src:arm-ball/axar-patel] Patel was signed up by the IPL franchise Mumbai Indians in 2013 but did not get a chance to play until he was released.
[src:arm-ball/axar-patel] He was then picked up by Kings XI Punjab in 2014 and had an impressive season with 17 wickets.
[src:arm-ball/axar-patel] He was retained by the Kings XI Punjab for the 2015 IPL season.
[src:arm-ball/axar-patel] Batting lower down the order, he scored 206 runs for the Kings XI Punjab in 2015 in addition to taking 13 wickets.
[src:arm-ball/axar-patel] On 1 May 2016, during a match against the Gujarat Lions, he took four wickets in five balls, including the first (and only) hat-trick of the 2016 IPL season, to pave the way for Kings XI Punjab's 23-run win against table-toppers Gujarat Lions in Rajkot.
[src:arm-ball/axar-patel] He was retained by Kings XI Punjab for the 2018 season.
[src:arm-ball/axar-patel] Axar Patel became the 9th Indian player to take a five-wicket haul on Test debut and only the second left-arm spinner after Dilip Doshi to take a five-for in his debut Test.
[src:arm-ball/axar-patel] In December 2018, he was signed up by the Delhi Capitals in the player auction for the 2019 Indian Premier League.
[src:arm-ball/axar-patel] He was retained by Delhi capitals for the 2021 season.
[src:arm-ball/axar-patel] After excellent performance in the 2014 IPL, Patel was rewarded with a place in the Indian ODI squad for the tour to Bangladesh and made his ODI debut in the first match of series at Sher-e-Bangla National Stadium and took 1/59 runs.
[src:arm-ball/axar-patel] He was part of India's 15-man squad for the 2015 Cricket World Cup.
[src:arm-ball/axar-patel] He made his Twenty20 International debut for India against Zimbabwe on 17 July 2015.
[src:arm-ball/axar-patel] He was named as a stand-by player for India's squad for the 2019 Cricket World Cup.
[src:arm-ball/axar-patel] In January 2021, Patel was named in India's Test squad for their series against England.
[src:arm-ball/axar-patel] He made his Test debut against England on 13 February 2021 and made his comeback in international cricket after a gap of almost three years.
[src:arm-ball/axar-patel] His first international Test wicket was of Joe Root.
[src:arm-ball/axar-patel] In the same match, he took a five wicket haul in England's second innings, becoming the ninth Indian bowler to do so on debut.
[src:arm-ball/axar-patel] In the 3 matches he played in his debut series, he took 27 wickets at a mere average of 10.59, finishing as the second-highest wicket taker of the series.
[src:arm-ball/axar-patel] Later in the year, he scored his maiden Test half-century against New Zealand.
[src:arm-ball/axar-patel] In September 2021, Patel was named in India's squad for the 2021 ICC Men's T20 World Cup.
[src:arm-ball/axar-patel] However, on 13 October 2021, he was replaced by Shardul Thakur in India's squad.
[src:arm-ball/axar-patel] In November 2021, Patel was named in India's squad for New Zealand's tour of India in 2021.
[src:arm-ball/axar-patel] In June 2022, Patel was named in India's squad for their T20I series against Ireland.
[src:arm-ball/axar-patel] On 25 July 2022, Patel scored his maiden ODI half-century against West Indies.
[src:arm-ball/axar-patel] He scored 64 runs off 35 balls, and remained unbeaten as he scored a match-winning six.
[src:arm-ball/axar-patel] In May 2024, he was named in India’s squad for the 2024 ICC Men's T20 World Cup tournament.
[src:arm-ball/axar-patel] In India's first match against Ireland, he took 1 wicket off just his one over.
[src:arm-ball/axar-patel] However, due to a quick run chase, he did not get a chance to bat.
[src:arm-ball/axar-patel] In India's second match against Pakistan, he took 1 wicket off his two overs, and made 20 runs off 18 balls with the bat.
[src:arm-ball/axar-patel] In India's third match against the United States, he took 1 wicket at the economy of 8.33.
[src:arm-ball/axar-patel] India's fourth match against Canada was washed out with a ball bowled.
[src:arm-ball/axar-patel] In India's first match of the Super 8, against Afghanistan, he made 12 off 6 and took 1 wicket at the economy of 5.00.
[src:arm-ball/axar-patel] In India's second match of the Super 8, against Bangladesh, he made 3 runs and did not take a wicket but bowled 2 overs at the economy of 13.00.
[src:arm-ball/axar-patel] In India's third and final match of the Super 8, against Australia, he did not bat, but took 1 wicket at the economy of 7.00.
[src:arm-ball/axar-patel] In the semi-final against England, he was named the POTM, making 10 runs and taking 3 wickets.
[src:arm-ball/axar-patel] In the final against South Africa, he was crucial, taking a wicket at the economy rate of 12.33 and making a quickfire 47 off 31, with 4 sixes and 1 four.
[src:arm-ball/axar-patel] He married Meha Patel on 26 January 2023 in Vadodara, Gujarat.
[src:arm-ball/axar-patel] He welcomed his son, Haksh, on 19 December 2024.
[src:arm-ball/batsman] In cricket, **batting** is the act or skill of hitting the ball with a bat to score runs and prevent the loss of one's wicket.
[src:arm-ball/batsman] Any player who is currently batting is, since September 2021, officially referred to as a **batter** regardless of whether batting is their particular area of expertise.
[src:arm-ball/batsman] Historically, *batsman* and *batswoman* were used, and these terms remain in widespread use.
[src:arm-ball/batsman] Batters have to adapt to various conditions when playing on different cricket pitches, especially in different countries; therefore, as well as having outstanding physical batting skills, top-level batters will have quick reflexes, excellent decision-making skills, and be good strategists.
[src:arm-ball/batsman] During an innings two members of the batting side are on the pitch at any time: the one facing the current delivery from the bowler is called the *striker*, while the other is the *non-striker*.
[src:arm-ball/batsman] When a batter is out, they are replaced by a teammate.
[src:arm-ball/batsman] This continues until the end of the innings, which in most cases is when 10 of the team members are out, whereupon the other team gets a turn to bat.
[src:arm-ball/batsman] Batting tactics and strategy vary depending on the type of match being played as well as the current state of play.
[src:arm-ball/batsman] The main concerns for the batters are not to lose their wicket and to score as many runs as quickly as possible.
[src:arm-ball/batsman] These objectives generally conflict—to score quickly, risky shots must be played, increasing the chance that the batter will be dismissed, while the batter's safest choice with a careful wicket-guarding stroke may be not to attempt any runs at all.
[src:arm-ball/batsman] Depending on the situation, batters may abandon attempts at run-scoring in an effort to preserve their wicket, or may attempt to score runs as quickly as possible with scant concern for the possibility of being dismissed.
[src:arm-ball/batsman] Unlike various other bat-and-ball sports, cricket batters may hit the ball in any direction to score runs, and can use creative shots to do so.
[src:arm-ball/batsman] As with all other cricket statistics, batting statistics and records are given much attention and provide a measure of a player's effectiveness.
[src:arm-ball/batsman] The main statistic for batting is a player's batting average.
[src:arm-ball/batsman] This is calculated by dividing the number of runs they have scored by the number of times they have been dismissed (not by the number of innings they have played).
[src:arm-ball/batsman] Any player, regardless of their area of special skill, is referred to as a "batter" (historically as a "batsman" or "batswoman") while they are batting.
[src:arm-ball/batsman] The batter's act of hitting the ball is called a "shot" or "stroke".
[src:arm-ball/batsman] A player who is selected for the team mainly for their batting skill is often referred to as simply a batter, regardless of whether they are currently batting, or sometimes as a specialist batter.
[src:arm-ball/batsman] A specialist bowler or wicket-keeper, on the other hand, would only be referred to as a batter when they are actually batting.
[src:arm-ball/batsman] In 2021, the Laws of Cricket were amended to officially use the term "batter" for gender neutrality, and this is increasingly the preferred term in some media outlets.
[src:arm-ball/batsman] A standard batting technique has been developed which is used by most batters.
[src:arm-ball/batsman] Technique refers to the batter's stance before the ball is bowled as well as the movement of the hands, feet, head, and body in the execution of a cricket stroke.
[src:arm-ball/batsman] The movement of the batter for a particular delivery depends on the shot being attempted.
[src:arm-ball/batsman] Front-foot shots are played with the weight on the front foot (left foot for a right-hander) and are usually played when the ball is pitched up to the batter, while back-foot shots are played putting the weight onto the back foot, usually to bowling that is pitched short.
[src:arm-ball/batsman] Shots may also be referred to as vertical or straight-bat shots, in which the bat is swung vertically at the ball (e.g. when playing a drive or leg glance), or horizontal or cross-bat shots, in which the bat is swung horizontally at the ball (e.g. when playing the pull or cut shot).
[src:arm-ball/batsman] While a batter is not limited in where or how they may hit the ball, the development of good technique has gone hand in hand with the development of a standard or orthodox cricket shots played to specific types of deliveries.
[src:arm-ball/batsman] These "textbook" shots are standard material found in many coaching manuals.
[src:arm-ball/batsman] The advent of limited overs cricket, with its emphasis on rapid run-scoring, has led to increasing use of unorthodox shots to hit the ball into gaps where there are no fielders.
[src:arm-ball/batsman] Unorthodox shots are typically—but not always—more high-risk than orthodox shots due to some aspects of good batting technique being abandoned.
[src:arm-ball/batsman] The stance is the position in which a batter stands to have the ball bowled to them.
[src:arm-ball/batsman] An ideal stance is "comfortable, relaxed and balanced", with the feet 40 centimetres (16 in) apart, parallel and astride the crease.
[src:arm-ball/batsman] Additionally, the front shoulder should be pointing down the wicket, the head facing the bowler, the weight equally balanced and the bat near the back toe.
[src:arm-ball/batsman] A slight crouch is adopted in order to be in a more effective striking posture whilst also isometrically loading the muscles; this allows the stroke to be played more dynamically.
[src:arm-ball/batsman] As the ball is about to be released, the batter will lift their bat up behind in anticipation of playing a stroke and will shift their weight onto the balls of their feet.
[src:arm-ball/batsman] By doing this they are ready to move swiftly into position to address the ball once they see its path out of the bowler's hand.
[src:arm-ball/batsman] Although the textbook, side-on stance is the most common, a few international players, such as Shivnarine Chanderpaul and Steve Smith, use an "open" or "square on" stance.
[src:arm-ball/batsman] Backlift is how a batter lifts their bat in preparation for hitting the ball.
[src:arm-ball/batsman] While the bat should be raised as vertically as possible, coaching manuals often suggest that correct technique is for the bat to be slightly angled from the perpendicular; a common instruction is to point the face of the bat in the direction of first or second slip.
[src:arm-ball/batsman] Some players (notably, in recent times, Brian Lara, Virender Sehwag) have employed an exaggerated backlift.
[src:arm-ball/batsman] Others, who have employed the more unorthodox open stance, such as Peter Willey, had a more abbreviated backlift.
[src:arm-ball/batsman] Depending upon the path of the ball, the batter will either move forward or back in their attempt to intercept it.
[src:arm-ball/batsman] A forward movement is designated a *front foot shot*, whereas a backward movement is designated a *back foot shot*.
[src:arm-ball/batsman] A front foot shot is typically used to address a ball arriving at between ankle and thigh height.
[src:arm-ball/batsman] The batter will step forward towards the ball, bending their front knee to bring the bat down to the anticipated height of the ball.
[src:arm-ball/batsman] By moving forward, the batter is also able to intercept the ball immediately after it has pitched, thus nullifying any potentially dangerous lateral movement.
[src:arm-ball/batsman] A back foot shot is typically used to address a ball arriving at between thigh and head height.
[src:arm-ball/batsman] The batter will step back and, if necessary, stand on their tiptoes to raise the bat to the height of the ball.
[src:arm-ball/batsman] By stepping back towards the wicket, the batter also receives the advantage of having an extra small amount of time to react to any unexpected lateral movement or variation in bounce.
[src:arm-ball/batsman] Vertical-bat or straight-bat shots can be played off either the front foot or the back foot depending upon the anticipated height of the ball at the moment it reaches the batter.
[src:arm-ball/batsman] The characteristic position of the bat is a vertical alignment at the point of contact.
[src:arm-ball/batsman] Vertical-bat shots are typically played with the batter's head directly above the point of contact so they are able to accurately judge the line of the ball.
[src:arm-ball/batsman] At this point, the bat can either be stationary and facing straight back down the wicket – known as a block or defensive shot; angled to one side – known as a glance or deflection; or travelling forwards towards the bowler – known as a drive.
[src:arm-ball/batsman] A *block* stroke is usually a purely defensive stroke designed to stop the ball from hitting the wicket or the batter's body.
[src:arm-ball/batsman] This shot has no strength behind it and is usually played with a light or "soft" grip (commentators often refer to "soft hands") and merely stops the ball moving towards the wicket.
[src:arm-ball/batsman] A block played on the front foot is known as a *forward defensive*, while that played on the back foot is known as a *backward defensive*.
[src:arm-ball/batsman] These strokes may be used to score runs, by manipulating the block to move the ball into vacant portions of the infield, in which case a block becomes a "push".
[src:arm-ball/batsman] Pushing the ball is one of the more common ways batters manipulate the strike.
[src:arm-ball/batsman] Leaving and blocking are employed much more often in first-class cricket (including Test matches), as there is no requirement to score runs as quickly as possible, thus allowing the batter to choose which deliveries to play.
[src:arm-ball/batsman] A *leg glance* is a delicate straight-batted shot played at a ball aimed slightly on the leg side, using the bat to flick the ball as it passes the batter, and requiring some wrist work as well, deflecting towards the square leg or fine leg area.
[src:arm-ball/batsman] The stroke involves deflecting the bat-face towards the leg side at the last moment, head and body moving inside the line of the ball.
[src:arm-ball/batsman] This shot is played "off the toes, shins or hip".
[src:arm-ball/batsman] It is played off the front foot if the ball is pitched up at the toes or shin of the batter, or off the back foot if the ball bounces at waist/hip height to the batter.
[src:arm-ball/batsman] Although the opposite term *off glance* is not employed within cricket, the concept of angling the bat face towards the offside to deflect the ball away from the wicket for the purpose of scoring runs through the off side is a commonly used technique.
[src:arm-ball/batsman] This would commonly be described instead as "running (or steering) the ball down to the third man".
[src:arm-ball/batsman] The *leave* is sometimes considered a cricket shot, even though the batter physically does not even touch the ball as it passes them.
[src:arm-ball/batsman] The leave is often used by a batter during the first few balls they receive, to give them time to judge the conditions of the pitch and the bowling before attempting to play a shot.
[src:arm-ball/batsman] Leaving a delivery is a matter of judgement and technique.
[src:arm-ball/batsman] The batter still has to watch the ball closely to ensure that it will not hit them or the wicket; they also have to ensure that their bat and hands are kept out of the path of the ball so that it cannot make accidental contact and possibly lead to them being out caught.
[src:arm-ball/batsman] Batters only leave the ball when they are certain that it will not hit the stumps.
[src:arm-ball/batsman] A *drive* is a straight-batted shot, played by swinging the bat in a vertical arc through the line of the ball, hitting the ball in front of the batter along the ground.
[src:arm-ball/batsman] It is one of the most common shots in a batter's armory and often the first shot taught to junior cricketers.
[src:arm-ball/batsman] Depending on the direction the ball travels, a drive can be a *cover drive* (struck towards the cover fielding position), an *off drive* (towards mid-off), *straight drive* (straight past the bowler), *on drive* (between stumps and mid-on) or *square drive* (towards point).
[src:arm-ball/batsman] A drive can also be played towards midwicket, although the phrase "midwicket drive" is not in common usage.
[src:arm-ball/batsman] Drives can be played both off the front and the back foot, but back-foot drives are harder to force through the line of the ball.
[src:arm-ball/batsman] Although most drives are deliberately struck along the ground to reduce the risk of being dismissed caught, a batter may decide to play a *lofted drive* to hit the ball over the infielders and potentially even over the boundary for six.
[src:arm-ball/batsman] A *flick* shot is a shot played on the leg side by flicking a full-length delivery using the wrists.
[src:arm-ball/batsman] The shot is played with the bat coming through straight as for the on drive, but the bat face is angled towards the leg side.
[src:arm-ball/batsman] It can be played both off the front foot or the back foot, either off the toes or from the hips.
[src:arm-ball/batsman] The shot is played between the mid-on and square leg region.
[src:arm-ball/batsman] Typically played along the ground, the flick can also be played by lofting the ball over the infield.
[src:arm-ball/batsman] The second class of cricket stroke comprises the horizontal-bat shots, also known as cross-bat shots: the cut, the square drive, the pull, the hook, and the sweep.
[src:arm-ball/batsman] Typically, horizontal bat shots have a greater probability of failing to make contact with the ball than vertical bat shots and therefore are restricted to deliveries that are not threatening to hit the stumps, either by dint of being too wide or too short.
[src:arm-ball/batsman] The bat is swung in a horizontal arc, with the batter's head typically not being perfectly in line with the ball at the point of contact.
[src:arm-ball/batsman] A *cut* is a cross-batted shot played at a short-pitched ball, placing it wide on the off side.
[src:arm-ball/batsman] The batter makes contact with the ball as it draws alongside or passes them and therefore requires virtually no effort on their part as they use the bowler's pace to divert the ball.
[src:arm-ball/batsman] A *square cut* is a shot hit into the off side at near to 90 degrees from the wicket (towards point).
[src:arm-ball/batsman] A *late cut* is played as or after the ball passes the batter's body and is hit towards the third man position.
[src:arm-ball/batsman] The cut shot is typically played off the back foot but is also sometimes played off the front foot against slower bowling.
[src:arm-ball/batsman] The cut should be played with the face of the bat rolling over the ball to face the ground thus pushing the ball downwards.
[src:arm-ball/batsman] A mistimed cut with an open-faced bat (with the face of the bat facing the bowler) will generally lead to the ball rising in the air, giving a chance for the batter to be caught.
[src:arm-ball/batsman] Although confusingly named a drive, the square drive is actually a horizontal bat shot, with identical arm mechanics to that of the square cut.
[src:arm-ball/batsman] A *pull* is a cross-batted shot played to a ball bouncing around waist height by swinging the bat in a horizontal arc in front of the body, *pulling* it around to the leg side towards mid-wicket or square leg.
[src:arm-ball/batsman] The term *hook* shot is used when the shot is played against a ball bouncing at or above chest high to the batter, the batter thus "hooking" the ball around behind square leg, either along the ground or in the air.
[src:arm-ball/batsman] Pull and hook shots can be played off the front or back foot, with the back foot being more typical.
[src:arm-ball/batsman] A *paddle sweep* shot is a sweep shot in which the ball is deflected towards fine leg with a stationary or near-stationary bat extended horizontally towards the bowler, whereas the hard sweep shot is played towards square leg with the bat swung firmly in a horizontal arc.
[src:arm-ball/batsman] Typically the sweep shot will be played to a legside delivery, but it is also possible for a batter to sweep the ball to the leg side from outside off stump.
[src:arm-ball/batsman] Attempting to sweep a full straight delivery on the stumps is generally not recommended because of the risk of lbw.
[src:arm-ball/batsman] Since a batter is free to play any shot to any type of delivery as they wish, the above list is by no means a complete list of the strokes that batters choose to play.
[src:arm-ball/batsman] Many unorthodox, typically high-risk, shots have been used throughout the history of the game.
[src:arm-ball/batsman] The advent of limited overs cricket has seen the increased use of unorthodox shots to hit the ball into gaps where there are no fielders placed.
[src:arm-ball/batsman] Unorthodox shots are rarely used in first-class cricket as the pace of the game is slower and it is relatively more important to keep one's wicket than to try to score runs off every ball.
[src:arm-ball/batsman] A few unorthodox shots have gained enough popularity or notoriety to have been given their own names and entered common usage.
[src:arm-ball/batsman] A reverse sweep is a cross-batted sweep shot played in the opposite direction to the standard sweep, thus instead of sweeping the ball to the leg side, it is swept to the off side, towards a *backward point* or *third man*.
[src:arm-ball/batsman] The batter may also swap their hands on the bat handle to make the stroke easier to execute.
[src:arm-ball/batsman] The batter may also bring their back foot to the front, therefore, turning the shot into a switch-hit and making it more like a traditional sweep.
[src:arm-ball/batsman] The advantage of a reverse sweep is that it effectively reverses the fielding positions and thus is very difficult to set a field to.
[src:arm-ball/batsman] It is also a risky shot for the batter as it increases the chance of lbw and also is quite easy to *top edge* to a fielder.
[src:arm-ball/batsman] It was first regularly played in the 1970s by the Pakistani batter Mushtaq Mohammad, though Mushtaq's brother Hanif Mohammad is sometimes credited as the inventor.
[src:arm-ball/batsman] Cricket coach Bob Woolmer has been credited with popularising the stroke.
[src:arm-ball/batsman] The most famous example of a reverse sweep backfiring was in the case of Mike Gatting of England against Allan Border of Australia in the 1987 Cricket World Cup Final.
[src:arm-ball/batsman] With England on course for victory, Gatting attempted a reverse sweep off the first delivery bowled by Border, top-edged the ball and was caught by wicketkeeper Greg Dyer.
[src:arm-ball/batsman] England subsequently lost momentum and eventually lost the match.
[src:arm-ball/batsman] Because of the unorthodox nature of hand and body position, it is often difficult to get a lot of power behind a reverse sweep; in many situations, the intention is to glance or cut the ball to the back leg area.
[src:arm-ball/batsman] However, on rare occasions, players have been able to execute reverse sweeps for a six.
[src:arm-ball/batsman] Kevin Pietersen, who pioneered switch-hitting, is adept at this, but one could argue that the resulting shot is basically a sweep rather than a reverse sweep.
[src:arm-ball/batsman] A more classic example of such a shot would be Yusuf Pathan's six off Robin Peterson.
[src:arm-ball/batsman] South Africa's AB de Villiers is well known for his ability to hit sixes with the reverse sweep at ease and Glenn Maxwell also often plays the reverse sweep.
[src:arm-ball/batsman] A *slog* is a powerful pull shot played over mid-wicket, usually, hit in the air in an attempt to score a six.
[src:arm-ball/batsman] A shot would be referred to as a slog when it is typically played at a delivery that would not ordinarily be pulled.
[src:arm-ball/batsman] A slog can also be described as hitting the ball to "cow corner".
[src:arm-ball/batsman] This phrase is designed to imply that the batter is unsophisticated in their stroke play and technique by suggesting they would be more at home playing on more rudimentary cricket fields in which there may be cows grazing along the boundary edge.
[src:arm-ball/batsman] The slog can be an effective shot because all the batter's power and body weight can be put into swinging the bat at the ball.
[src:arm-ball/batsman] A *slog sweep* is a slog played from the kneeling position used to sweep.
[src:arm-ball/batsman] Slog sweeps are usually directed over square-leg rather than to mid-wicket.
[src:arm-ball/batsman] It is almost exclusively used against reasonably full-pitched balls from slow bowlers, as only then does the batter have time to sight the length and adopt the kneeling position required for the slog sweep.
[src:arm-ball/batsman] The front leg of the shot is usually placed wider outside leg stump to allow for a full swing of the bat.
[src:arm-ball/batsman] An *upper cut* is a shot played towards *third man*, usually hit when the ball is pitched outside the *off stump* with extra bounce.
[src:arm-ball/batsman] It is a dangerous shot which can *edge* the ball to keeper or slips if not executed correctly.
[src:arm-ball/batsman] The shot is widely used in modern cricket.
[src:arm-ball/batsman] The shot is advantageous on fast bouncy tracks and is seen commonly in Twenty20 cricket.
[src:arm-ball/batsman] Notable players who used the upper cut include Sachin Tendulkar, Virender Sehwag and Brendan Taylor.
[src:arm-ball/batsman] A *switch hit* is a shot where a batter changes their handedness and posture to adopt a stance the mirror image of their traditional handedness while the bowler is running in to bowl.
[src:arm-ball/batsman] As a fielding team cannot manoeuvre fielders while the bowler is in their run-up, the fielding side is effectively wrong-footed with the fielders out of position.
[src:arm-ball/batsman] The shot was pioneered by Kevin Pietersen, first performed off the bowling of Muttiah Muralitharan in England's 2006 home series against Sri Lanka.
[src:arm-ball/batsman] It was subsequently used in the New Zealand series in England in 2008 when Pietersen performed the shot twice in the same over against Scott Styris on his way to making an unbeaten century.
[src:arm-ball/batsman] David Warner, the Australian opener, is also a frequent user of the switch hit and used it to great effect against the Indian off-spinner Ravichandran Ashwin in the first Twenty20 of the Indian cricket team's tour to Australia 2012.
[src:arm-ball/batsman] Glenn Maxwell and Ben Stokes also play the switch hit.
[src:arm-ball/batsman] The legality of the switch hit was questioned when first introduced but cleared by the International Cricket Council as legal.
[src:arm-ball/batsman] The shot is risky because a batter is less proficient in the other handedness and is more likely to make a mistake in the execution of the shot.
[src:arm-ball/batsman] A *scoop* shot has been used by a number of first-class players.
[src:arm-ball/batsman] It is played to short-pitched straight balls that would traditionally be defended or, more aggressively, pulled to the leg side.
[src:arm-ball/batsman] To play a scoop shot, the batter is on the front foot and aims to get beneath the bounce of the ball and hit it directly behind the stumps, up and over the wicket-keeper.
[src:arm-ball/batsman] This shot, though risky in the execution, has the advantage of being aimed at a section of the field where a fielder is rarely placed – particularly in Twenty20 and One Day International cricket where the number of outfielders is limited.
[src:arm-ball/batsman] However, the Marillier shot is played over the batter's shoulder to fine leg, but the basis of the scoop stroke is for the batter to go down on one knee to a good length or slightly short-of-length delivery off a fast or medium paced bowler and scoop the ball over the head of the wicket-keeper.
[src:arm-ball/batsman] The scoop shot is a risky shot to play as the improper execution of this shot may lead to a catch being offered.
[src:arm-ball/batsman] A version of the scoop stroke called the *Dilscoop* was developed by Sri Lankan right-handed batter Tillakaratne Dilshan during the 2009 ICC World Twenty20.
[src:arm-ball/batsman] The *helicopter shot* is the act of hitting the ball by means of a wristy flick, using the bottom-hand as the dominant force.
[src:arm-ball/batsman] The shot gets its name from the flourish completing the stroke, with the bat being circled overhead.
[src:arm-ball/batsman] The shot got its fame through MS Dhoni, who played it on a regular basis as a way to score boundaries against full and yorker length deliveries.
[src:arm-ball/batsman] The *French cut* is a stroke where the ball is hit with the inside edge of the bat, meaning it is directed between the batter and the stumps, and moves away in the direction of the fine leg fielding position.
[src:arm-ball/batsman] The stroke is very difficult to play intentionally, and is more often a mistake by the batter.
[src:arm-ball/batsman] It is a risky stroke, and can easily result in the batter playing on to their stumps, resulting in the batter being dismissed as bowled.
[src:arm-ball/batsman] The fundamental aim of each batter is to find a means of safely scoring runs against each bowler they face.
[src:arm-ball/batsman] To do this, the batter must take into consideration the bowler's strategy, the position of the fielders, the pitch conditions, and their own strengths and weaknesses.
[src:arm-ball/batsman] The strategy they will decide on will incorporate a number of preconceived attacking responses to the various deliveries they may anticipate receiving, designed specifically to score runs with minimal risk of being dismissed.
[src:arm-ball/batsman] The success of this strategy will be dependent upon both the accuracy of its conception and the technical ability with which it is carried out.
[src:arm-ball/batsman] A key aspect of the strategy of batting is the trade-off between the level of aggression (trying to score) and the risk involved of being dismissed.
[src:arm-ball/batsman] An optimal batting strategy balances several considerations: the number of wickets left, the target that has been set (if batting last) and how the risk of losing a wicket increase when increasing the strike rate.
[src:arm-ball/batsman] These strategies depend on the match situation and on the match format.
[src:arm-ball/batsman] Strategies therefore vary greatly between the three forms of international cricket: Test, One Day International and T20 cricket.
[src:arm-ball/batsman] In Test cricket, the usual aim is to score as high a total as possible.
[src:arm-ball/batsman] As the overs are unlimited, a batter can take their time to score runs.
[src:arm-ball/batsman] In general, 90 overs have to be bowled per day in Test match cricket.
[src:arm-ball/batsman] The first-drop batter is usually also chosen for their sound technique, so as to stabilise their end in case an opener gets out.
[src:arm-ball/batsman] The middle order of a batting team in Test matches usually includes its most skilled batters in terms of shot-playing ability, because during the middle overs of a day batting is relatively easier than in the initial stages of the innings.
[src:arm-ball/batsman] If the batting innings of a team begins after the last half-hour of the day, the team might employ a nightwatchman to bat after a dismissal.
[src:arm-ball/batsman] The *nightwatchman* is usually a lower-order player, able to protect their wicket primarily by defending dangerous balls and leaving non-dangerous ones rather than looking to produce a large number of runs for their team, but not a complete rabbit, liable to expose other players late in a day.
[src:arm-ball/batsman] In the third innings, the batting team may score quickly to set a large target to the opposition.
[src:arm-ball/batsman] This scenario usually occurs on the fourth day's play.
[src:arm-ball/batsman] The batting captain decides how many overs they are prepared to allow the opposition to chase the batting team's total in their fourth innings.
[src:arm-ball/batsman] The captain usually declares their team's innings at a predetermined time on the fourth day so they can bowl at least 20 overs on that day and 90 overs on the last day.
[src:arm-ball/batsman] A good number of overs to bowl at the opposition team in the fourth innings is essential because usually on the fourth and fifth days of a Test match conditions are good for bowling (especially slow bowling), with the pitch having experienced a fair degree of wear and tear.
[src:arm-ball/batsman] Thus, to make the target as difficult as possible, the batting side speeds up the run rate (runs per over) until the captain declares.
[src:arm-ball/batsman] If, however, a batting team is significantly behind the opposition in terms of runs going into the fourth day of a Test match, a typical strategy by the batting team involves playing defensively to avoid losing their wickets.
[src:arm-ball/batsman] This ensures that they occupy the most time until the match draws to a close on the fifth day, because if a team's innings does not end on the fifth day then the match is *drawn*, or a stalemate is reached.
[src:arm-ball/batsman] As One Day International matches have a limited set of overs, batters try to score quickly.
[src:arm-ball/batsman] Doing so, batters should aim for a higher run rate than the one which would maximise their expected personal score.
[src:arm-ball/batsman] It is optimal for batters to take the risk of being dismissed and being replaced by another teammate.
[src:arm-ball/batsman] This higher risk strategy makes the best of the limited number of overs.
[src:arm-ball/batsman] Scoring quickly typically means trying to score at least one run per ball bowled.
[src:arm-ball/batsman] Most batter manage to score at an average of four runs an over (i.e. four runs in the six ball over).
[src:arm-ball/batsman] The optimal level of risk should vary depending on different factors.
[src:arm-ball/batsman] It should be higher when the team has more wickets left as they provide of a cushion of security (against the risk of ending all out).
[src:arm-ball/batsman] It should be higher when the pitch provides good conditions for batting, making it easier to score without great risk of being dismissed.
[src:arm-ball/batsman] It should increase towards the end of the innings when the number of overs left is small (there is not much to lose in taking the risk of ending all out).
[src:arm-ball/batsman] Research has shown that teams broadly follow these principles.
[src:arm-ball/batsman] A noticeable exception is when batters face the possibility of scoring a personal milestone (e.g. century), in that case, they tend to decrease their risk-taking below what is optimal for the team in order to increase their chance of reaching the milestone.
[src:arm-ball/batsman] When a team goes out to bat, the best players bat first.
[src:arm-ball/batsman] The first three batters (number 1, 2, 3) are known as the *top order*; the next four (numbers 4, 5, 6 and possibly 7) form the *middle order*, and the last four (numbers 8, 9, 10 and 11) are the *lower order* or *tail*.
[src:arm-ball/batsman] The specialist batters of a team usually bat near the top of the order, so as to score more runs.
[src:arm-ball/batsman] The *openers* or opening batter are the first two players to take the crease.
[src:arm-ball/batsman] They are not necessarily the best batters, but are expected to negotiate the new ball and not lose wickets until the shine on the ball is considerably diminished (a hard and shiny ball bounces and swings more and is more difficult for the batter to face).
[src:arm-ball/batsman] In addition, they are supposed to play quick innings (more runs in fewer balls), reflecting the fact that the fielding side is subject to restrictions on the placement of fielders in the first 15 overs which makes it easier to score runs.
[src:arm-ball/batsman] In a recent amendment to the rules of ODI cricket, fielding captains are given mandatory fielding restrictions for the first 10 overs and then two chunks of 5 overs each, also known as *power-play* overs, which they may impose at any stage of their choice within the stipulated 50 overs.
[src:arm-ball/batsman] Their job is to take over from the openers and typically play a careful and prolonged innings, effectively tying up one end of the batting.
[src:arm-ball/batsman] This brings in some stability in the batting, as new batters find it difficult to settle down and it helps to have a settled player at the other end.
[src:arm-ball/batsman] The best batter of the team is usually put at number 3 or 4, to protect them from the difficulties of batting against the best bowlers on a fresh pitch and to allow them to play long innings.
[src:arm-ball/batsman] The middle order is often considered the most valuable asset of a batting line-up in One-Day Internationals because its members are responsible for consolidating the batting team's position through the middle part of the 50 overs.
[src:arm-ball/batsman] Characteristic of middle-order batting is the practice of taking many *singles* (or *ones*) and 'twos', with only the occasional *boundary* (a four or a six), as opposed to the more flamboyant openers who score primarily in boundaries.
[src:arm-ball/batsman] This is because the fielding restrictions on the opposition are lifted in the middle overs so that the percentage of boundaries scored decreases.
[src:arm-ball/batsman] Middle-order players are often chosen for the ability to run hard and fast between the wickets (to maximise the number of runs not scored from boundaries) and for their endurance and patience.
[src:arm-ball/batsman] The middle order typically sets the stage for an aggressive assault on the bowling in the final 10 overs of the match.
[src:arm-ball/batsman] To achieve this assault, two things are necessary – a number of hard-hitting players yet to bat or not out and a number of wickets in hand (since aggression means a greater likelihood of losing wickets).
[src:arm-ball/batsman] The last 10 overs of a one-day cricket match innings is often the most exciting part of the innings, because of a large number of boundaries scored and wickets taken.
[src:arm-ball/batsman] During the last ten overs of an ODI, batters often use shots that are riskier than shots played at the beginning of the innings.
[src:arm-ball/batsman] Examples of risky shots include the reverse sweep and the paddle-scoop.
[src:arm-ball/batsman] These shots are used to achieve a boundary which would not be possible when playing a safer, more orthodox shot.
[src:arm-ball/batsman] Finally, the lower order consists of the bowlers of the team, who are not known for their batting prowess and so bat as low down the order as possible.
[src:arm-ball/batsman] However, there are no real restrictions to the batting positions.
[src:arm-ball/batsman] Captains have been known to experiment with the batting line-up to gain specific advantages.
[src:arm-ball/batsman] When batting, a batter has to balance opportunities to score runs by running between the popping creases with the risk of being run out (or even stumped, if batting outside their crease).
[src:arm-ball/batsman] Batting partners must agree on each run they take, or else one of them is likely to be out of their ground and thus run out.
[src:arm-ball/batsman] Sometimes batters take risks by running even when the fielder has the ball in hand, and is in a position to throw the ball at the wicket; this is known as "taking on the arm of the fielder".
[src:arm-ball/batsman] This can occasionally lead to overthrows.
[src:arm-ball/batsman] Batters often slide headfirst with their bat outstretched to make their ground.
[src:arm-ball/batsman] Being able to run faster to score more runs, as well as improve endurance so as to not be fatigued by running a lot throughout a long innings (which could disrupt the concentration or strength needed for batting), is part of the athletic training for batters.
[src:arm-ball/bouncer-cricket] In the sport of cricket, a **bouncer** (or **bumper**) is a type of short-pitched delivery, usually bowled by a fast bowler, which bounces once and reaches the batter around shoulder or head height.
[src:arm-ball/bouncer-cricket] Bouncers are used to push the batter back on to their back foot if she or he has been freely playing front-foot scoring shots, such as drives.
[src:arm-ball/bouncer-cricket] To this end, bouncers are usually directed more or less at the line of the batter's body.
[src:arm-ball/bouncer-cricket] Aiming at the batter is legal provided the ball bounces on the pitch; or, when it reaches the batter without bouncing of the pitch (a full toss), the ball is below the batter's waist.
[src:arm-ball/bouncer-cricket] Aiming at the batter's head without bouncing on the pitch, known as a beamer, is illegal.
[src:arm-ball/bouncer-cricket] A batter may play a bouncer in either a defensive or an attacking way.
[src:arm-ball/bouncer-cricket] If the batter plays it defensively he aims primarily to avoid getting out, and secondarily to avoid being hit by the ball.
[src:arm-ball/bouncer-cricket] For a head-high bouncer, these goals are achieved most easily by ducking under the ball.
[src:arm-ball/bouncer-cricket] If the ball is at chest height, the batter's best defence is to move on to his back foot, raise his bat vertically to chest height, and attempt to block the ball and direct it downwards to the pitch so as to avoid presenting a catch to a fielder.
[src:arm-ball/bouncer-cricket] Sometimes the batter will need to jump into the air to gain the necessary height to defend with the bat.
[src:arm-ball/bouncer-cricket] Given these approaches, the bowler can hope to both intimidate the batter somewhat, and possibly have the ball deflect off the bat at an awkward angle and produce a catch for a nearby fielder.
[src:arm-ball/bouncer-cricket] Conversely, the bouncer can be a very productive ball for the batter, if he plays it in an attacking manner.
[src:arm-ball/bouncer-cricket] The shot that is used to attack the bouncer is the hook shot.
[src:arm-ball/bouncer-cricket] To play the hook shot the batter moves his back foot backwards and towards the off side as the ball is being delivered.
[src:arm-ball/bouncer-cricket] As the ball approaches, the batter swivels from facing the off side to facing the leg side, while holding the bat horizontally.
[src:arm-ball/bouncer-cricket] The batter's aim is to hit the ball at high speed towards, into or over the leg side boundary.
[src:arm-ball/bouncer-cricket] However, despite their run-scoring potential, hook shots frequently lead to wickets falling, particularly through balls hitting the top edge of the bat and being caught by leg side fielders.
[src:arm-ball/bouncer-cricket] However, if the bouncer is misdirected by the bowler, and reaches the batter on the off side of his wicket, the cut, uppercut or late cut can be played, either with the intention of guiding the ball along the ground, through a gap in the field setting or over the infield for four or six.
[src:arm-ball/bouncer-cricket] There is an unspoken agreement, particularly in the time before the widespread use of batting helmets, that fast bowlers will not bowl bouncers at each other, because less skilled batters are less likely to effectively defend and therefore more likely to be struck.
[src:arm-ball/bouncer-cricket] Breaking of this rule can lead to "bouncer wars" – that is, the targeted bowler engaging in retaliatory hostile short-pitched bowling at his opponent during the following innings.
[src:arm-ball/bouncer-cricket] Because of the potential danger to batters of being hit and to stop bowlers bowling bouncers all the time, there are Laws in the Laws of Cricket governing how frequently a bowler may bowl bouncers, as well as how many fielders may field backward of square leg.
[src:arm-ball/bouncer-cricket] These laws take into account the relative skill of the batters.
[src:arm-ball/bouncer-cricket] During the 1970s to 1980s, bouncers were used as part of a team's intimidatory tactics, especially by the West Indies team.
[src:arm-ball/bouncer-cricket] In 1991, the International Cricket Council (ICC) introduced a "one bouncer per batter per over" rule in an attempt to discourage the use of intimidation.
[src:arm-ball/bouncer-cricket] However, the ruling was not well received by players and umpires alike, with English umpire Dickie Bird describing it as "farcical" as he felt that calling intimidatory tactics should be left to the umpire.
[src:arm-ball/bouncer-cricket] The ICC changed it to two bouncers per over in 1994, with a two-run no-ball penalty (rather than one-run no-ball) if the bowler exceeded two bouncers an over.
[src:arm-ball/bouncer-cricket] One Day International cricket allowed one bouncer per over in 2001 (and a one-run no-ball in case a bowler exceeded the limit).
[src:arm-ball/bouncer-cricket] On 29 October 2012 the ICC increased the number of bouncers that could be bowled during a One Day International to two per over.
[src:arm-ball/bouncer-cricket] The number of bouncers per over allowed in T20s was kept to one.
[src:arm-ball/bouncer-cricket] Fast leg theory, the deliberate and sustained bowling of bouncers aimed at the body, coupled with a cordon of legside catching fieldsmen to catch deflections, was a tactic used by England against Australia in 1932/33, dubbed the Bodyline series by the Australians.
[src:arm-ball/bouncer-cricket] It caused a sporting and political firestorm between the mother country and the former colony and several incidents threatened to boil over into public riots.
[src:arm-ball/bouncer-cricket] This controversial tactic caused the Laws of Cricket to be reformed to prevent any recurrence.
[src:arm-ball/bouncer-cricket] In 1954–55 in Sydney, England fast bowler Frank Tyson bowled bouncers at Australian Ray Lindwall, who returned the favour by hospitalising Tyson with one of his own.
[src:arm-ball/bouncer-cricket] An angry Tyson returned with a large lump on his head and took 6/85 in the second innings to give England a 38-run victory.
[src:arm-ball/bouncer-cricket] In 1994 at the Oval Devon Malcolm was hit on the helmet by a bouncer from Fanie de Villiers.
[src:arm-ball/bouncer-cricket] The incensed Malcolm told the South Africans "You guys are history" and took apart their second innings with 9/57.
[src:arm-ball/bouncer-cricket] The bouncer is an aggressive delivery and the very nature of the delivery by a fast bowler and aimed at the head can lead to batters being hit in the chest, neck or head.
[src:arm-ball/bouncer-cricket] While rare, impacts to the top part of the body can cause serious injuries or even death.
[src:arm-ball/bouncer-cricket] While the laws of cricket can be used to limit the delivery, particularly when being used against specialist bowlers at the end of the batting order, it is not outright banned like the beamer.
[src:arm-ball/bouncer-cricket] In 1962, Indian captain Nari Contractor was hit above his right ear by a Charlie Griffith bouncer which resulted in severe loss of blood and left Contractor critically ill.
[src:arm-ball/bouncer-cricket] He regained full consciousness after six days and returned to first-class cricket ten months later.
[src:arm-ball/bouncer-cricket] While originally there was fears that, due to the impact of the ball and the shattered glass, Hawke may have lost sight in his right eye, he was soon released from the hospital with bruising and minor cuts, returning to the field several hours later as a spectator.
[src:arm-ball/bouncer-cricket] The image of Bob Hawke recoiling from the hit was subsequently circulated in Australian Media.
[src:arm-ball/bouncer-cricket] In 2006, playing in his 100th test, Australian opener Justin Langer was struck on the head by a bouncer from Makhaya Ntini and hospitalised.
[src:arm-ball/bouncer-cricket] In 2008 West Indies batter Shivnarine Chanderpaul was knocked out for several minutes after being hit by a bouncer from Australian fast bowler Brett Lee during a test match.
[src:arm-ball/bouncer-cricket] Shoaib Akhtar injured both Gary Kirsten (2003) and Brian Lara (2004) with fast bouncers.
[src:arm-ball/bouncer-cricket] Both batters had to be taken off the field.
[src:arm-ball/bouncer-cricket] In November 2014, Australian cricketer Phillip Hughes was knocked unconscious by a bouncer from Sean Abbott, which hit the side of his head, between the grille and shell of his helmet, during a Sheffield Shield match.
[src:arm-ball/bouncer-cricket] He was taken to hospital in a critical condition, suffering from a subarachnoid haemorrhage, but died from his injuries two days later, never having regained consciousness.
[src:arm-ball/bouncer-cricket] During the semi-final of the 2019 Cricket World Cup, against England, Alex Carey injured his chin from a bouncer bowled by Jofra Archer.
[src:arm-ball/bouncer-cricket] The resulting blow knocked the helmet off Carey's head; he caught it mid-air before it could fall onto the stumps, saving himself from dismissal.
[src:arm-ball/bouncer-cricket] During the second test of the 2019 Ashes Series, Australian batter Steve Smith was hit on the neck by a 148.7 km/h (92.4mph) delivery from England fast bowler Jofra Archer.
[src:arm-ball/bouncer-cricket] After retiring concussed, Smith returned to play 45 minutes later.
[src:arm-ball/bouncer-cricket] The Australian medical team's decision to let him play was criticised by the brain injury charity Headway, as "incredibly dangerous".
[src:arm-ball/bouncer-cricket] Smith's replacement, Marnus Labuschagne, became the first concussion substitute in a Test match.
[src:arm-ball/bowler-cricket] In cricket, **bowling** is the action of propelling the ball toward the wicket defended by a batter.
[src:arm-ball/bowler-cricket] A player skilled at bowling is called a *bowler*; a bowler who is also a competent batter is known as an *all-rounder*.
[src:arm-ball/bowler-cricket] Bowling the ball is distinguished from *throwing* the ball, which is not allowed, by a strictly specified biomechanical definition, which restricts the angle of extension of the elbow.
[src:arm-ball/bowler-cricket] A single act of bowling the ball towards the batter is called a *ball* or a *delivery*.
[src:arm-ball/bowler-cricket] Bowlers bowl deliveries in sets of six, called an *over*.
[src:arm-ball/bowler-cricket] Once a bowler has bowled an over, a teammate will bowl an over from the other end of the pitch.
[src:arm-ball/bowler-cricket] The Laws of Cricket govern how a ball must be bowled.
[src:arm-ball/bowler-cricket] If a ball is bowled illegally, an umpire will rule it a *no-ball*.
[src:arm-ball/bowler-cricket] If a ball is bowled too wide of the striker for the batter to be able to play at it with a proper cricket shot, the bowler's end umpire will rule it a *wide*.
[src:arm-ball/bowler-cricket] There are different types of bowlers, from fast bowlers, whose primary weapon is pace, through swing and seam bowlers who try to make the ball deviate in its course through the air or when it bounces, to slow bowlers, who will attempt to deceive the batter with a variety of flight and spin.
[src:arm-ball/bowler-cricket] A spin bowler usually delivers the ball quite slowly and puts spin on the ball, causing it to turn at an angle while bouncing off the pitch.
[src:arm-ball/bowler-cricket] A team can be said to have elected to "have a bowl" when it wins the coin toss and chooses to field.
[src:arm-ball/bowler-cricket] In the early days of cricket, underarm bowling was the only method employed.
[src:arm-ball/bowler-cricket] Many theories exist about the origins of cricket.
[src:arm-ball/bowler-cricket] One suggests that the game began among shepherds hitting a stone or a ball of wool with their crooks and, at the same time, defending the wicket gate into the sheep-fold (from Anglo Saxon 'cricce', a crooked staff).
[src:arm-ball/bowler-cricket] A second theory suggests the name came from a low stool known as a 'cricket' in England, which from the side looked like the long, low wicket used in the early days of the game (originally from the Flemish 'krickstoel', a low stool on which parishioners knelt in church).
[src:arm-ball/bowler-cricket] There is also a reference to 'criquet' in North-East France in 1478 and evidence that the game evolved in South-East England in the Middle Ages.
[src:arm-ball/bowler-cricket] In 1706 William Goldwyn published the first description of the game.
[src:arm-ball/bowler-cricket] He wrote that two teams were first seen carrying their curving bats to the venue, choosing a pitch and arguing over the rules to be played.
[src:arm-ball/bowler-cricket] They pitched two sets of wickets, each with a "milk-white" bail perched on two stumps; tossed a coin for first knock, the umpire called "play" and the "leathern orb" was bowled.
[src:arm-ball/bowler-cricket] They had four-ball overs, the umpires leant on their staves (which the batters had to touch to complete a run), and the scorers sat on a mound making notches.
[src:arm-ball/bowler-cricket] The first written "Laws of Cricket" was drawn up in 1744.
[src:arm-ball/bowler-cricket] They stated, "the principals shall choose from amongst the gentlemen present two umpires who shall absolutely decide all disputes.
[src:arm-ball/bowler-cricket] The stumps must be 22 inches high and the bail across them six inches.
[src:arm-ball/bowler-cricket] The ball must be between 5 & 6 ounces, and the two sets of stumps 22 yards apart".
[src:arm-ball/bowler-cricket] There were no limits on the shape or size of the bat.
[src:arm-ball/bowler-cricket] It appears that 40 notches was viewed as a very big score, probably due to the bowlers bowling quickly at shins unprotected by pads.
[src:arm-ball/bowler-cricket] The world's first cricket club was formed in Hambledon in the 1760s and the Marylebone Cricket Club (MCC) was founded in 1787.
[src:arm-ball/bowler-cricket] During the 1760s and 1770s it became common to pitch the ball through the air, rather than roll it along the ground.
[src:arm-ball/bowler-cricket] This innovation gave bowlers the weapons of length, deception through the air, plus increased pace.
[src:arm-ball/bowler-cricket] It also opened new possibilities for spin and swerve.
[src:arm-ball/bowler-cricket] In response, batters had to master timing and shot selection.
[src:arm-ball/bowler-cricket] One immediate consequence was the replacement of the curving bat with the straight one.
[src:arm-ball/bowler-cricket] All of this raised the premium on skill and lessened the influence of rough ground and brute force.
[src:arm-ball/bowler-cricket] It was in the 1770s that the modern game began to take shape.
[src:arm-ball/bowler-cricket] The weight of the ball was limited to between five and a half and five and three-quarter ounces, and the width of the bat to four inches.
[src:arm-ball/bowler-cricket] The latter ruling followed an innings by a batter called Thomas "Daddy" White, who appeared with a bat the width of the wicket.
[src:arm-ball/bowler-cricket] In 1774, the first leg before law was published.
[src:arm-ball/bowler-cricket] Also around this time, a third stump became commonplace.
[src:arm-ball/bowler-cricket] By 1780, the duration of a first-class cricket match was generally three days, and this year also saw the creation of the first six-seam cricket ball.
[src:arm-ball/bowler-cricket] In 1788, the MCC published its first revision of the laws, which prohibited charging down an opponent and also provided for mowing and covering the wicket to standardise conditions.
[src:arm-ball/bowler-cricket] The desire for standardisation reflected the massive increase in the popularity of cricket during the 18th century.
[src:arm-ball/bowler-cricket] Between 1730 and 1740, 150 cricket matches were recorded in the papers of the time.
[src:arm-ball/bowler-cricket] The 19th century saw a series of significant changes.
[src:arm-ball/bowler-cricket] The circumference of the ball was specified for the first time in 1838 (its weight had been dictated 60 years earlier).
[src:arm-ball/bowler-cricket] Pads, made of cork, became available for the first time in 1841, and these were further developed following the invention of vulcanised rubber, which was also used to introduce protective gloves in 1848.
[src:arm-ball/bowler-cricket] In the 1870s, boundaries were introduced – previously, all hits had to be run; if the ball went into the crowd, the spectators would clear a way for the fieldsman to fetch it.
[src:arm-ball/bowler-cricket] The biggest change, however, was in how the ball was delivered by the bowler.
[src:arm-ball/bowler-cricket] At the start of the century, all bowlers were still delivering the ball under-arm.
[src:arm-ball/bowler-cricket] However, so the story goes, John Willes became the first bowler to use a "round-arm" technique after practising with his sister Christina, who had used the technique, as she was unable to bowl underarm due to her wide dress impeding her delivery of the ball.
[src:arm-ball/bowler-cricket] The round-arm action came to be employed widely in matches but was quickly determined to be illegal and banned by the MCC, who stated that "the ball must be delivered underhand, not thrown or jerked, with the hand underneath the elbow at the time of delivering the ball".
[src:arm-ball/bowler-cricket] When it was accepted the rules stated that the arm could not be raised above the shoulder.
[src:arm-ball/bowler-cricket] It was quickly found, however, that a raised arm imparted more accuracy and generated more bounce than the roundarm method.
[src:arm-ball/bowler-cricket] Again, the governing body banned the method.
[src:arm-ball/bowler-cricket] It was not until the method was finally accepted by the MCC in 1835 that it grew rapidly in popularity amongst all players.
[src:arm-ball/bowler-cricket] Underarm bowling hitherto had almost disappeared from the game.
[src:arm-ball/bowler-cricket] An infamous "underarm bowling incident" occurred during a match in 1981, in which the Australian bowler, Trevor Chappell, took advantage of the fact that underarm bowling was still legal by rolling the ball along the ground.
[src:arm-ball/bowler-cricket] By doing so he avoided the possibility that the New Zealand batter, Brian McKechnie, would score a six from the last ball to tie the match, as the bat would not be able to hit the ball high enough to score a six.
[src:arm-ball/bowler-cricket] As a result of this incident underarm bowling was subsequently made illegal in all grades of cricket, except by prior agreement of both teams, as it was not considered to be within the spirit of the game.
[src:arm-ball/bowler-cricket] Bowling the ball is distinguished from simply throwing the ball by a strictly specified biomechanical definition.
[src:arm-ball/bowler-cricket] Originally, this definition said that the elbow joint must not straighten out during the bowling action.
[src:arm-ball/bowler-cricket] Bowlers generally hold their elbows fully extended and keeping the bowling arm straight, releasing it near the top of the arc.
[src:arm-ball/bowler-cricket] Flexion at the elbow is not allowed, but any extension of the elbow was deemed to be a throw and would be liable to be called a no-ball.
[src:arm-ball/bowler-cricket] This was thought to be possible only if the bowler's elbow was originally held in a slightly flexed position.
[src:arm-ball/bowler-cricket] In 2005, this definition was deemed to be physically impossible by a scientific investigative commission.
[src:arm-ball/bowler-cricket] Biomechanical studies that showed that *almost* all bowlers extend their elbows somewhat throughout the bowling action, because the stress of swinging the arm around *hyperextends* the elbow joint.
[src:arm-ball/bowler-cricket] A guideline was introduced to allow extensions or hyperextensions of angles up to 15 degrees before deeming the ball illegally thrown.
[src:arm-ball/bowler-cricket] Bowling actions are typically divided into *side on* and *front on* actions.
[src:arm-ball/bowler-cricket] In the side on action, the back foot lands parallel to the bowling crease and the bowler aims at the wicket by looking over his front shoulder.
[src:arm-ball/bowler-cricket] In the front on action, the back foot lands pointing down the pitch and the bowler aims at the wicket by looking inside the line of his front arm.
[src:arm-ball/bowler-cricket] Many bowlers operate with a *mid-way* action with the back foot landing at roughly 45 degrees and the upper body aligned somewhere between side on and front on.
[src:arm-ball/bowler-cricket] This differs from a *mixed* action, which mixes distinct elements of both side on and front on actions, and is generally discouraged amongst young bowlers as it can lead to problems in later life due to the twisting of the back inherent in the action.
[src:arm-ball/bowler-cricket] In a game of cricket, the ultimate priority of the fielding side is to restrict the total number of runs scored by the batting side, and the actions of the bowlers will be fundamental to achieving this objective.
[src:arm-ball/bowler-cricket] The primary means of achieving this is by dismissing the batting side by getting all ten of the opposition wickets as quickly as possible.
[src:arm-ball/bowler-cricket] A secondary objective will be to keep the batting side's run rate as low as possible.
[src:arm-ball/bowler-cricket] In fact, in most forms of cricket, the twin aims of the fielding side are targeted concurrently, as the achievement of one aim tends to have a positive effect upon the other.
[src:arm-ball/bowler-cricket] Taking regular opposition wickets will remove the better batters from the crease, typically leading to a slowing of the scoring rate.
[src:arm-ball/bowler-cricket] Conversely, slowing the scoring rate can put additional pressure on the batters and force them into taking extra risks, which will often lead to wickets.
[src:arm-ball/bowler-cricket] Depending upon the format of the match, these two strategies will be given different weights.
[src:arm-ball/bowler-cricket] In an unlimited, timed or declaration match, the main aim of the bowling attack will be to take wickets, so attacking bowling and fielding strategies will be used.
[src:arm-ball/bowler-cricket] In a limited overs match, this aim will also be supplemented by the secondary need to prevent the batting side from scoring quickly, so more defensive strategies will be used.
[src:arm-ball/bowler-cricket] In general, the shorter the number of overs per side, the more priority will be given to this secondary target of maintaining a low run-rate.
[src:arm-ball/bowler-cricket] It is also highly probable that the need for attacking or defensive strategies can switch frequently as a cricket match progresses.
[src:arm-ball/bowler-cricket] It is the sign of a good cricket captain to be able to tell which strategy is most appropriate in any set of circumstances and the best way of implementing it.
[src:arm-ball/bowler-cricket] The simultaneous twin objectives of bowling are to take wickets and prevent run scoring opportunities.
[src:arm-ball/bowler-cricket] Both objectives are achieved through the underlying aim of bowling the ball in such a way that the batter is unable to connect with the ball in the middle of the bat and control its movement after contact.
[src:arm-ball/bowler-cricket] A good bowler may be able to combine two of these skills, a truly great bowler may be able to combine all three.
[src:arm-ball/bowler-cricket] The fundamental skill of bowling on a good length incorporates the ability to pitch the ball such a distance from the batter that he is unable to move forward and drive the ball on the half volley, and is also unable to step back and play the ball on the back foot.
[src:arm-ball/bowler-cricket] This removes many of the batter's attacking options, and also increases the probability of misjudging a delivery and losing the wicket.
[src:arm-ball/bowler-cricket] A good length delivery is one in which the ball has had sufficient time to move far enough off the pitch to beat the bat but the batter has not had time to react to the movement and adjust the shot.
[src:arm-ball/bowler-cricket] The faster the bowler and the greater the movement he is able to generate, the larger the area of the pitch that can be designated an effective "good" length.
[src:arm-ball/bowler-cricket] Other areas of the pitch may also often be used as a variation to a good length delivery.
[src:arm-ball/bowler-cricket] But the height of an attempted yorker or full toss must not be higher than the batter's waist, or else it will be called a no-ball beamer, which could have bowlers banned from the match.
[src:arm-ball/bowler-cricket] The line a bowler chooses to bowl will depend on several factors: the movement he is generating on the ball, the shots the batter is able to play, and the field the captain has set.
[src:arm-ball/bowler-cricket] The two most common tactics are to either bowl directly at the stumps, or to bowl 3 inches to 6 inches outside the line of off stump.
[src:arm-ball/bowler-cricket] Bowling at the stumps is an attacking tactic with the intention of dismissing the batter bowled or lbw.
[src:arm-ball/bowler-cricket] It can also be used as a defensive tactic, as the batter will feel less able to play risky shots knowing that he will be dismissed should he miss the ball.
[src:arm-ball/bowler-cricket] Bowling outside off stump is known as *the corridor of uncertainty*.
[src:arm-ball/bowler-cricket] When done well, this line may confuse the batter into whether to defend the ball or leave it, and may tempt him to play away from his body with his head not in line with the ball.
[src:arm-ball/bowler-cricket] The main aim of this tactic is to dismiss the batter caught by the wicketkeeper or in the slips.
[src:arm-ball/bowler-cricket] Other bowling variations, such as bowling wide of off stump or bowling at leg stump are generally seen as negative and defensive tactics.
[src:arm-ball/bowler-cricket] Other than the ability to land the ball on a strategically optimum line and length, the main weapons of the bowler are his ability to move the ball sideways as it approaches the batter and his ability to deliver the ball at a high velocity.
[src:arm-ball/bowler-cricket] The velocities of cricket bowlers vary between 40 and 100 mph (64 and 161 km/h).
[src:arm-ball/bowler-cricket] In professional cricket, a bowler in the 40–60 mph range would be said to be a slow bowler, in the 60–80 mph range a medium pace bowler, and a bowler 80 mph+ a fast bowler.
[src:arm-ball/bowler-cricket] In the amateur game, these distinctions would be approximately 10 mph slower.
[src:arm-ball/bowler-cricket] Many professional fast bowlers are able to reach speeds of over 85 mph, with a handful of bowlers in the world able to bowl at 95 mph+.
[src:arm-ball/bowler-cricket] The ability to react to a cricket ball travelling at 85 mph is a skill that only professional and high level amateur cricketers possess.
[src:arm-ball/bowler-cricket] The pace of a bowler not only challenges the reaction speed of the batter, but also his physical courage.
[src:arm-ball/bowler-cricket] Fast bowlers are able to exploit this by bowling bouncers, either regularly or as an occasional surprise delivery.
[src:arm-ball/bowler-cricket] Bowlers are also able to get the ball to move sideways by using either *spin* or *swing*.
[src:arm-ball/bowler-cricket] Adding a spin to a cricket ball will make it deviate due to the Magnus effect in its flight (like a slider in baseball), and then produce sideways movement off the ground.
[src:arm-ball/bowler-cricket] Swing is obtained by using air pressure differences caused by angling the seam of the cricket ball to produce a lateral movement in the air.
[src:arm-ball/bowler-cricket] Fast bowlers will generally only use swing to obtain movement, but medium pace and slow bowlers will often use a combination of the two.
[src:arm-ball/bowler-cricket] The intention is that in creating movement in the delivery, the batter will misjudge the line of the ball as it arrives, causing him to miss it entirely, in which case he may be dismissed bowled or lbw, or miss-hit it, in which case he may be out caught.
[src:arm-ball/bowler-cricket] To avoid becoming predictable, a bowler will typically bowl a variety of different deliveries with different combinations of pace and movement.
[src:arm-ball/bowler-cricket] A tactically astute bowler may be able to spot a potential weakness in a batter that a particular delivery may be able to exploit.
[src:arm-ball/bowler-cricket] Bowlers will often also bowl deliveries in preplanned sets, with the intention of dismissing the batter with the final delivery in the set.
[src:arm-ball/bowler-cricket] This is known as "setting a trap" for the batter. batters and bowlers will often also engage in a game of "cat and mouse", in which the bowler varies his tactics to try to trap and dismiss the batter, but the batter also keeps adjusting his tactics in response.
[src:arm-ball/bowler-cricket] In limited overs cricket, there is a limitation on the number of overs each bowler can bowl.
[src:arm-ball/bowler-cricket] This number depends on the match length, and is usually 20% of the total overs in the innings.
[src:arm-ball/bowler-cricket] For example, the usual limit for twenty-over cricket is four overs per bowler, for forty-over cricket eight per bowler and for fifty-over cricket ten per bowler.
[src:arm-ball/bowler-cricket] There is, however, no limit on the number of overs each bowler may bowl in first-class cricket matches, except that no two overs can be bowled consecutively thus restricting any one bowler from a maximum of 50% (plus 1 over) of each innings total.
[src:arm-ball/bowler-cricket] The rule also applies in terms of breaks within a Test innings (Drinks, Lunch and Tea breaks, end of day and beginning of next day).
[src:arm-ball/bowler-cricket] The rule can only be broken if one finishes the end of the previous match starts the next match.
[src:arm-ball/carrom-ball] The **carrom ball** is a style of spin bowling delivery used in cricket.
[src:arm-ball/carrom-ball] The ball is released by flicking it between the thumb and a bent middle finger in order to impart spin.
[src:arm-ball/carrom-ball] The first bowler known to have used this style of delivery was the Australian Jack Iverson from Victoria, who used it throughout his Test cricket career in the period after the Second World War, although he did not use the name "carrom ball".
[src:arm-ball/carrom-ball] Fellow Australian John Gleeson used a similar grip a decade later, but by the end of the 1970s the method was almost forgotten.
[src:arm-ball/carrom-ball] It has since re-entered cricketing consciousness because of its use by Ajantha Mendis of Sri Lanka, with the new name of carrom ball.
[src:arm-ball/carrom-ball] Mendis unveiled this delivery during the 2008 Asia Cup.
[src:arm-ball/carrom-ball] Sri Lankan Rangana Herath is believed to be the first left handed spin bowler to have used the method in international cricket, dismissing Australian opener David Warner with a delivery in the carrom ball style during a test match.
[src:arm-ball/carrom-ball] The ball is held between the thumb, forefinger and the middle finger and, instead of a conventional release, the ball is squeezed out and flicked by the fingers like a carrom player flicking the disc on a carrom board.
[src:arm-ball/carrom-ball] It is different from wrist-bowled deliveries.
[src:arm-ball/carrom-ball] Traditional leg-spin is bowled with anti-clockwise wrist movement for a right-armed bowler.
[src:arm-ball/carrom-ball] A finger-bowled delivery such as traditional off-spin is bowled with a clockwise finger movement.
[src:arm-ball/carrom-ball] In a carrom delivery, the middle finger and thumb flick or squeeze the ball out of the hand, like a carrom player flicking a striker in the indoor game of carrom.
[src:arm-ball/carrom-ball] When the center finger is gripped towards the leg side, the ball spins from leg to off; when the center finger is gripped towards the off side, the ball spins from off to leg.
[src:arm-ball/carrom-ball] Depending on the degree the ball is gripped towards the leg side, the carrom ball could also travel straight.
[src:arm-ball/carrom-ball] The carrom ball can therefore spin to either the off or leg sides or travel straight (as opposed to the misconception that it only spins towards the off side).
